{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780128888376,"sessionID":"ses_1880d6cd9ffemrYJzfC1U23ohw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_ircfj3eaerq2_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/state-parts/iter-001.jsonl"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/state-parts/iter-001.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":1,\"model\":\"minimax\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.6,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"iter1\"}\n\n(End of file - total 1 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":1,\"model\":\"minimax\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.6,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"iter1\"}","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/state-parts/iter-001.jsonl","time":{"start":1780128888369,"end":1780128888375}},"id":"prt_e77f334ae001LsDGHaMeAciARz","sessionID":"ses_1880d6cd9ffemrYJzfC1U23ohw","messageID":"msg_e77f311fc001dEtRgsKtTzw4Eq"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780128888681,"sessionID":"ses_1880d6cd9ffemrYJzfC1U23ohw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_ircfj3eaerq2_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/deltas/iter-001.jsonl"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/deltas/iter-001.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":1,\"model\":\"minimax\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.6,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"iter1\"}\n2: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-1\",\"label\":\"Skill router is self-referential — primary measurement target\",\"iteration\":1}\n3: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-2\",\"label\":\"Three pluggable seams determine Lane C insertion point\",\"iteration\":1}\n4: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-3\",\"label\":\"Lane-aware resource org creates observable surface\",\"iteration\":1}\n5: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-4\",\"label\":\"sk-doc validates shape Lane C measures behavior\",\"iteration\":1}\n6: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-5\",\"label\":\"skill-advisor operates at different layer than Lane C\",\"iteration\":1}\n7: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-6\",\"label\":\"Coverage (skill-on minus skill-off) is fundamental usefulness metric\",\"iteration\":1}\n8: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-7\",\"label\":\"Tau-Bench trace capture applies to routing observation\",\"iteration\":1}\n9: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-8\",\"label\":\"Tool retrieval P/R maps directly to routing P/R\",\"iteration\":1}\n10: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-9\",\"label\":\"LLM-as-judge has circularity risk must be mitigated\",\"iteration\":1}\n11: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-10\",\"label\":\"Five scoring dimensions operationalized D1-D5\",\"iteration\":1}\n12: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-11\",\"label\":\"Normalization via fractional per-skill plus complexity weighting\",\"iteration\":1}\n13: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-12\",\"label\":\"loop-host.cjs mode=skill-benchmark is correct entry point\",\"iteration\":1}\n\n(End of file - total 13 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":1,\"model\":\"minimax\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.6,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"iter1\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-1\",\"label\":\"Skill router is self-referential — primary measurement target\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-2\",\"label\":\"Three pluggable seams determine Lane C insertion point\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-3\",\"label\":\"Lane-aware resource org creates observable surface\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-4\",\"label\":\"sk-doc validates shape Lane C measures behavior\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-5\",\"label\":\"skill-advisor operates at different layer than Lane C\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-6\",\"label\":\"Coverage (skill-on minus skill-off) is fundamental usefulness metric\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-7\",\"label\":\"Tau-Bench trace capture applies to routing observation\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-8\",\"label\":\"Tool retrieval P/R maps directly to routing P/R\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-9\",\"label\":\"LLM-as-judge has circularity risk must be mitigated\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-10\",\"label\":\"Five scoring dimensions operationalized D1-D5\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-11\",\"label\":\"Normalization via fractional per-skill plus complexity weighting\",\"iteration\":1}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i1-12\",\"label\":\"loop-host.cjs mode=skill-benchmark is correct entry point\",\"iteration\":1}","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/deltas/iter-001.jsonl","time":{"start":1780128888670,"end":1780128888680}},"id":"prt_e77f33632001mznJvAF7COYiiL","sessionID":"ses_1880d6cd9ffemrYJzfC1U23ohw","messageID":"msg_e77f311fc001dEtRgsKtTzw4Eq"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780128888756,"sessionID":"ses_1880d6cd9ffemrYJzfC1U23ohw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"webfetch","callID":"call_function_ircfj3eaerq2_3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.08144"},"output":"\\[2404.08144\\] LLM Agents can Autonomously Exploit One-day Vulnerabilities                              \n\n[Skip to main content](#content)\n\n[![Cornell University](/static/browse/0.3.4/images/icons/cu/cornell-reduced-white-SMALL.svg)](https://www.cornell.edu/)\n\n[Learn about arXiv becoming an independent nonprofit.](https://tech.cornell.edu/arxiv/)\n\nWe gratefully acknowledge support from the Simons Foundation, [member institutions](https://info.arxiv.org/about/ourmembers.html), and all contributors. [Donate](https://info.arxiv.org/about/donate.html)\n\n[](/IgnoreMe)\n\n[![arxiv logo](/static/browse/0.3.4/images/arxiv-logo-one-color-white.svg)](/) \\> [cs](/list/cs/recent) \\> arXiv:2404.08144\n\n[Help](https://info.arxiv.org/help) | [Advanced Search](https://arxiv.org/search/advanced)\n\nAll fields Title Author Abstract Comments Journal reference ACM classification MSC classification Report number arXiv identifier DOI ORCID arXiv author ID Help pages Full text\n\n Search\n\n[![arXiv logo](/static/browse/0.3.4/images/arxiv-logomark-small-white.svg)](https://arxiv.org/)\n\n  [![Cornell University Logo](/static/browse/0.3.4/images/icons/cu/cornell-reduced-white-SMALL.svg)](https://www.cornell.edu/)\n\n   GO\n\n## quick links\n\n-   [Login](https://arxiv.org/login)\n-   [Help Pages](https://info.arxiv.org/help)\n-   [About](https://info.arxiv.org/about)\n\n# Computer Science > Cryptography and Security\n\n**arXiv:2404.08144** (cs)\n\n\\[Submitted on 11 Apr 2024 ([v1](https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.08144v1)), last revised 17 Apr 2024 (this version, v2)\\]\n\n# Title:LLM Agents can Autonomously Exploit One-day Vulnerabilities\n\nAuthors:[Richard Fang](https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&query=Fang,+R), [Rohan Bindu](https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&query=Bindu,+R), [Akul Gupta](https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&query=Gupta,+A), [Daniel Kang](https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&query=Kang,+D)\n\nView a PDF of the paper titled LLM Agents can Autonomously Exploit One-day Vulnerabilities, by Richard Fang and 3 other authors\n\n[View PDF](/pdf/2404.08144) [HTML (experimental)](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.08144v2)\n\n> Abstract:LLMs have becoming increasingly powerful, both in their benign and malicious uses. With the increase in capabilities, researchers have been increasingly interested in their ability to exploit cybersecurity vulnerabilities. In particular, recent work has conducted preliminary studies on the ability of LLM agents to autonomously hack websites. However, these studies are limited to simple vulnerabilities.  \n> In this work, we show that LLM agents can autonomously exploit one-day vulnerabilities in real-world systems. To show this, we collected a dataset of 15 one-day vulnerabilities that include ones categorized as critical severity in the CVE description. When given the CVE description, GPT-4 is capable of exploiting 87% of these vulnerabilities compared to 0% for every other model we test (GPT-3.5, open-source LLMs) and open-source vulnerability scanners (ZAP and Metasploit). Fortunately, our GPT-4 agent requires the CVE description for high performance: without the description, GPT-4 can exploit only 7% of the vulnerabilities. Our findings raise questions around the widespread deployment of highly capable LLM agents.\n\nSubjects:\n\nCryptography and Security (cs.CR); Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI)\n\nCite as:\n\n[arXiv:2404.08144](https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.08144) \\[cs.CR\\]\n\n \n\n(or [arXiv:2404.08144v2](https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.08144v2) \\[cs.CR\\] for this version)\n\n \n\n[https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2404.08144](https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2404.08144)\n\nFocus to learn more\n\narXiv-issued DOI 